Cache Eviction Policies:
“Cache eviction policies determine which items to remove when cache is full, with common strategies like LRU, LFU, FIFO, and TTL depending on access patterns.”
LRU (Least Recently Used):-Cache: A B C D  Access: A, B → D is least used → evict D
LFU (Least Frequently Used):-Remove item with lowest access frequency. A(5), B(2), C(1) → evict C
FIFO (First In First Out):-Remove oldest inserted item.Inserted: A → B → C → evict A
LIFO (Last In First Out):-Remove most recently added item.i.e.Rarely used
TTL (Time To Live):-Remove items after specific time.Cache user session → expire after 30 mins

Throttling :
API Throttling is a technique used in system design to control the rate at which API requests are processed. It temporarily limits the number of requests a client 
can make in a given time frame to prevent sudden traffic spikes or server overload. By enforcing throttling, systems ensure that resources are used efficiently 
and consistently, avoiding potential downtime caused by excessive demand. Throttling is typically applied to manage burst traffic, maintaining the availability 
and performance of the API for all users while preventing a single client from consuming too many resources.

Rate limiting and throttling both manage API traffic, but differ in their approach: rate limiting strictly blocks excess requests (often with a 429 error) over a 
time period, whereas throttling delays or queues requests to smoothly handle traffic spikes. Rate limiting is ideal for enforcing usage quotas, while throttling 
ensures service availability under heavy load. 

Rate Limiting :-
Rate limiting is a technique to limit network traffic to prevent users from exhausting system resources. Ratelimiter restricts attackers to flooding a target system 
with requests and consuming too much network capacity, storage, and memory.APIs that use rate limiting can throttle or temporarily block any client that tries 
to make too many API calls. It might slow down a throttled user’s requests for a specified time or deny them altogether. Rate limiting ensures that legitimate 
requests can reach the system and access information without impacting the overall application’s performance.
why: Rate limiting is a crucial part of a modern cybersecurity strategy. It addresses several attack techniques that affect the incoming request rate.
A DDoS(Distributed Denil of Service) attack attempts to overwhelm the target system with traffic, making it unavailable to legitimate users. Rate limiting mitigates DDoS threats by 
preventing any given traffic source from sending too many requests.
How : Rate limiting works within applications, not in the web server. Rate limiting typically involves tracking the IP addresses where requests originate 
and identifying the time lapsed between requests. IP addresses are the application’s main way to identify who has made each request.
Types of Rate Limits : user rate limit, geographics rate limit, server rate limit
Algo used for  Ratelimit :
A.) Token Bucket:--The Token Bucket algorithm is a flexible rate-limiting method that controls the flow of data or requests by using a metaphorical bucket filled 
with "tokens." Unlike rigid algorithms that enforce a constant speed, it allows for bursty traffic while maintaining a controlled long-term average rate
B.) Fixed Window Rate limit :--restrict the number of requests allowed during a given timeframe (window)
c.) Leaky Bucket Rate Limiting :-They focus on the fixed length of request queues without considering the time. The server will service requests on a first-come, 
first-serve basis. New requests join the back of the queue. The server will drop a new request if it arrives when the queue is full

