Tradational Hashing :In a simple hash-based load balancing system, a user's request might be directed to a server using the formula 
server = hash(user_id) % N (where N is the number of servers). This approach works well as long as N is constant
Consistent Hashing:-Consistent Hashing is a distributed system technique used to evenly distribute data across multiple servers (or nodes) in a 
way that minimizes data movement when nodes are added or removed.
It is widely used in distributed databases, caching systems, and microservices architectures, Loadbalancer.

Why Do We Need Consistent Hashing?
In distributed systems (like distributed caches or databases), we need to:
Distribute data across multiple machines
Scale horizontally (add/remove servers)
Maintain availability
Minimize data reshuffling
With traditional hashing, if you use:
server = hash(key) % N
When N (number of servers) changes, almost all keys get remapped.
This causes massive data movement and cache invalidation.

Consistent hashing solves this problem.
How Consistent Hashing Works
1️⃣ Hash Ring Concept
Imagine a circular hash space (0 to 2³² – 1).
Both servers and data keys are hashed into this ring.
Each key is assigned to the next server clockwise on the ring.
2️⃣ Node Addition
When a new server is added:
Only the keys between the new server and its previous neighbor are reassigned.
Other keys remain unaffected.
3️⃣ Node Removal
When a server is removed:
Only its keys move to the next server.
Rest of the system remains unchanged.
👉 Only about 1/N keys move, instead of almost all keys.

Use consistent hashing when:
You need stable key → node mapping
You want minimal data movement
You have stateful routing requirements
Avoid it when:
Your system is fully stateless
External storage handles state
Simpler load balancing works
