What Is a Sticky Session?
A sticky session (also called session affinity) is a load-balancing technique where:
Once a user’s request is routed to a particular server instance, subsequent requests from that same user are sent to the same server.
Instead of distributing every request randomly, the load balancer “sticks” a client to one backend.
How It Works:-
Sticky sessions are typically implemented at the load balancer layer using:
Cookies (e.g., server inserts a session cookie)
IP-hash routing
Custom header–based routing

Why Sticky Sessions Exist:
Originally used when applications were stateful.
Example:
User logs in
Session stored in server memory
Next request must go to same server
Otherwise, session is lost
