What is Consistent Hashing?
🎯 Answer
Consistent Hashing is a technique used to distribute data across multiple nodes such that when a node is added or removed, 
only a minimal amount of data is re-distributed.

✅ Why do we need Consistent Hashing?
Problem with normal hashing
index = hash(key) % N
👉 If number of servers (N) changes:
Almost all keys get remapped
Causes cache misses & data movement
✅ Consistent Hashing solves:
Minimal data movement
Better scalability
High availability

✅ How it works (Simple Explanation)
Imagine a circular ring (0–2³²)
Servers and keys are placed on ring using hash
Each key is assigned to the next clockwise server
Example
Ring:
[Server A] ---- [Server B] ---- [Server C]
Key K → goes to nearest server clockwise
👉 If Server B is removed:
Only keys between A → B move to C
Rest unaffected ✅

✅ Virtual Nodes (Important Interview Point)
Problem:
Uneven distribution
Solution:
👉 Each server has multiple virtual nodes
Example:
Server A → A1, A2, A3
Server B → B1, B2, B3
✔ Better load balancing
✔ Avoid hotspots

✅ Where is it used?
1. Distributed Caching
Redis cluster
Memcached
👉 Key → mapped to cache node
2. Distributed Databases
Apache Cassandra
Amazon DynamoDB
👉 Data partitioning across nodes
3. Load Balancing
Request routing to servers
4. Microservices / API Gateway
Session stickiness
Request routing

✅ When to use Consistent Hashing?
Use it when:
Nodes are frequently added/removed
Need horizontal scaling
Want minimal data reshuffling
Handling large distributed systems

✅ Real-world Example
🎯 Scenario: Distributed Cache
Users → API → Cache Cluster (3 nodes)
Without Consistent Hashing:
Add 1 node → 100% cache invalidated ❌
With Consistent Hashing:
Only ~1/N keys move ✅

✅ Code Concept (Java - simplified)
int hash = key.hashCode();
SortedMap<Integer, String> ring = new TreeMap<>();

// find next node clockwise
Integer node = ring.ceilingKey(hash);
if (node == null) {
    node = ring.firstKey();
}
✅ Interview One-Liner (Very Important)

“Consistent Hashing is used in distributed systems to ensure minimal data movement when nodes scale up or down, making it ideal for
caching, databases, and load balancing.”
